(271, 1, 'component/debug', 'Debug component', '<div class="section" id="debug-component">\n\n<div class="section" id="usage">\n<h2>Usage<a class="headerlink" href="#usage" title="Permalink to this headline">&para;</a></h2>\n<p>If you want to dump huge objects in twig, and you cannot do it with default <code>dump()</code> function, you can use next way.\nStart listen for xDebug connections and add next construction to your twig template:</p>\n<div class="highlight-html+jinja"><div class="highlight"><pre><span class="cp">{%</span> <span class="k">do</span> <span class="nv">ite_debug</span><span class="o">()</span> <span class="cp">%}</span> <span class="c">{# for all variables in context #}</span>\n</pre></div>\n</div>\n<p>or</p>\n<div class="highlight-html+jinja"><div class="highlight"><pre><span class="cp">{%</span> <span class="k">do</span> <span class="nv">ite_debug</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="nv">form</span><span class="o">,</span> <span class="nv">entity</span><span class="o">)</span> <span class="cp">%}</span> <span class="c">{# for specific variables #}</span>\n</pre></div>\n</div>\n<p>xDebug will automatically emits a breakpoint to the debug client on the specific line, and you can check your variable\nvalues in <code>$variables</code> var.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n', '<ul>\n<li><a class="reference internal" href="#usage">Usage</a></li>\n</ul>', 1, '[{"link":"..\\/","title":"Components"}]', '{"link":"..\\/validation\\/","title":"Validation component"}', '{"link":"..\\/..\\/plugin\\/","title":"Plugins"}');
